                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d847">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/3319a: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Chargé in China</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Tenney</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1920-03-26T14:00:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">March 26, 1920—2 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>69. Repeat to Consul General at Hankow. Press despatch from Tokyo reports
                    “American marines who landed at Kiukiang at the request of British Consul killed
                    two Chinese coolies according to reports here. They later withdrew at the
                    request of local authorities.” Despatch says landing was to quell fight between
                    Chinese policemen and coolies and that feeling against Americans and Europeans
                    is intense as a result of incident.</p>
                <p>Investigate and report facts to Department promptly.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Colby</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
